# Line endings, for the files where they are not cosmetic.
#
# deploy/ is read by Linux. A CR at the end of a shebang makes the kernel look for an interpreter
# literally named "bash\r" and answer "bad interpreter: No such file or directory" — on a file that
# looks perfect in every editor and greps fine. setup-ssl.sh is the one that hurts: it would fail
# at the top, so the certificate is never requested at all.
#
# This is not a hypothetical tidy-up. Every file below is currently `i/lf w/crlf`: LF in the index,
# CRLF in the working tree on Windows. That works today only because the people committing happen
# to run core.autocrlf=true, which normalises on the way in. That is a setting on their machine,
# not a property of this repo — one clone with autocrlf=false commits CRLF into the index and the
# server breaks, with no local symptom to notice it by.
#
# Checked before adding this file: nothing in the index has CRLF or mixed endings, so these rules
# describe what is already there and renormalise nothing.

* text=auto

*.sh       text eol=lf
*.service  text eol=lf
*.conf     text eol=lf
*.mjs      text eol=lf
*.mts      text eol=lf

# Windows reads these; CRLF is what they want.
*.cmd      text eol=crlf
*.ps1      text eol=crlf

# Fonts and images: never touch the bytes. fonts.data.ts is generated from these — a single
# altered byte and the PDF renders in a fallback face.
*.woff  binary
*.woff2 binary
*.ttf   binary
*.otf   binary
*.png   binary
*.jpg   binary
*.jpeg  binary
*.ico   binary
*.pdf   binary
